{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1224,"record_hash":"sha256:195612de93d4fa0f6fdf2c444c0bbd86fe10561016752fe4c04693ba7efd9ff9","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:26:10.735Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 44b3a7\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1600\nOutput:\n```text\none session -> many capture turns -> many records\n```\n\nA session remains the durable project-scoped object. A turn represents one\ncapture invocation, usually one observed agent stop-hook run. Transcript records\nremain the normalized conversation/tool events that `but-agentlog` already\nstores and deduplicates.\n\nThis is deliberately not:\n\n```text\nbranch -> session -> records\n```\n\nBranches, changes, commits, and pull requests should still reference sessions or\nturns. They should not own transcript data.\n\nIn this document, \"turn\" means **capture turn** unless explicitly qualified. A\ncapture turn is the durable storage unit. UI/read paths may still render\n**conversation turns** or **provider turns** inside a capture turn, especially\nfor handoff and backfilled sessions.\n\n## What A Turn Means\n\nA session turn is the unit of \"what we observed this time.\"\n\nEvery time the capture flow runs:\n\n1. parse the transcript snapshot\n2. deduplicate against already stored record hashes\n3. append only new transcript records\n4. write a turn object describing this capture invocation\n5. record which transcript records belong to the turn\n6. record enough repository environment state to support later association\n\nCreate a session turn only when capture writes at least one new transcript\nrecord. An environment-only observation should not create a turn. Otherwise the\nmodel drifts from agent-session capture into repository telemetry.\n\nThe first hook run for a session may capture more than one actual conversation\nturn if it imports an existing transcript backlog. Later stop-hook runs should\nusually map more closely to one user/agent interaction. That distinction should\nstay visible in the model: a turn is a capture observation, not necessarily a\nprovider-native turn.\n\nFor first-time backfill, create one capture turn containing all newly written\nrecords and one environment snapshot from capture time. Provider-native turn\nidenti\n[TRUNCATED]\nrovider id.\n\nMinimum useful fields:\n\n- turn id\n- session key\n- source key\n- capture kind\n- capture timestamp\n- transcript record membership, probably by record hash and/or source record\n  index\n- optional provider turn key on transcript records, for grouping/display only\n- previous turn reference, when there is a previous capture turn in the same\n  session\n- environment snapshot\n\nThe record membership matters because `but-agentlog` already deduplicates\nrecords. Without turn membership, repeated hook capture preserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\n`TurnDetail.records` must be an ordered array. That order is authoritative for\nrendering records within a capture turn; hashes and source indexes identify the\nrecords, but they are not a replacement for sequence.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part of turn identity. It exists to make interval\nevidence cheap to evaluate, for example \"worktree files seen in the previous\nturn later appeared in commits visible in this turn.\" The first turn omits the\nfield.\n\nImplementation should write transcript records, record hashes, the turn object,\nthe turn list entry, and derived index entries as one logical GitMeta update.\nIf transcript record writes can succeed while the turn write fails, a later\nretry may see zero new records and skip the missing turn.\n\nCapture should also have a simple concurrency rule. Either hold a repo/session\ncapture lock around dedupe, previous-turn lookup, and write, or use optimistic\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:26:10.735Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}